{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3e1d5c62-52b1-412d-8bcc-0bbe3c793f31","content":"The project isn't in the current directory, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for VS Code agent mode.\n\nCreate **`.vscode/mcp.json`** in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`dotnet run --project`** — builds and launches the server automatically.\n- For a published build, replace with `\"command\": \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer\"` (adjust TFM as needed).\n\n**Make sure** your MCP server reads from stdin and writes to stdout (e.g., using the `ModelContextProtocol` or `Microsoft.Extensions.AI` SDK with `stdio` transport). Any logging must go to **stderr**, not stdout, to avoid corrupting the MCP protocol.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5435c588-2ac3-44e9-9c43-c7a37088561f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet. The user said they built it, but it's not in the current directory. That's fine — they're asking how to configure `mcp.json`, not asking me to build the server. Let me just give them the configuration guidance.\n\nFor a C# MCP server using stdio transport (which is the standard for local MCP servers), the `mcp.json` configuration in VS Code would look something like this:","outputTokens":417,"requestId":"8438:291A22:FAF250:13BC184:69FFDAC0"},"id":"3f982f86-a930-4a29-99ec-4c7c47c7983d","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:09:30.053Z","parentId":"4868fed0-9072-46eb-a20a-f9c0835c8e60"}
